    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p><a href=\"http://neo4j.org/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://neo4j.org/</a> is a graph database that contains many of graph algorithms and scales better than most in-memory libraries.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 613477,
      "reputation" : 61,
      "user_id" : 342449,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fdf636822750a458d38489a58a1a72a6?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "xyz",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/342449/xyz"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "community_owned_date" : 1420749501,
    "score" : 7,
    "last_activity_date" : 1274026993,
    "creation_date" : 1274026993,
    "answer_id" : 2844481,
    "question_id" : 51574,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p><a href=\"http://incubator.apache.org/hama/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://incubator.apache.org/hama/</a> is a distributed scientific package on Hadoop for massive matrix and graph data.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 622639,
      "reputation" : 1,
      "user_id" : 359160,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a2f7d0215a08179f77ee159aef57daf3?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Bob",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/359160/bob"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "community_owned_date" : 1420749501,
    "score" : -1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1275737221,
    "creation_date" : 1275737221,
    "answer_id" : 2980129,
    "question_id" : 51574,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>JGraph from <a href=\"http://mmengineer.blogspot.com/2009/10/java-graph-floyd-class.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">http://mmengineer.blogspot.com/2009/10/java-graph-floyd-class.html</a></p>\n\n<p>Provides a powerfull software to work with graphs (direct or undirect). Also generates Graphivz code, you can see graphics representations. You can put your own code algorithms into pakage, for example: backtracking code. The package provide some algorithms: Dijkstra, backtracking minimun path cost, ect.. </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 467725,
      "reputation" : 20887,
      "user_id" : 873282,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 55,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1e6ae94f84a34641ccc5abc86a664694?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "koppor",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/873282/koppor"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "community_owned_date" : 1420749501,
    "score" : 15,
    "last_activity_date" : 1501068029,
    "last_edit_date" : 1501068029,
    "creation_date" : 1369249477,
    "answer_id" : 16699707,
    "question_id" : 51574,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Apache Commons offers <a href=\"http://commons.apache.org/sandbox/commons-graph/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">commons-graph</a>. Under  <a href=\"http://svn.apache.org/viewvc/commons/sandbox/graph/trunk/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://svn.apache.org/viewvc/commons/sandbox/graph/trunk/</a> one can inspect the source. Sample API usage is <a href=\"http://svn.apache.org/viewvc/commons/sandbox/graph/trunk/src/test/java/org/apache/commons/graph/model/BaseMutableGraphTestCase.java?view=markup\" rel=\"noreferrer\">in the SVN</a>, too. See <a href=\"https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SANDBOX-458\" rel=\"noreferrer\">https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SANDBOX-458</a> for a list of implemented algorithms, also compared with Jung, GraphT, Prefuse, <a href=\"https://github.com/jbpt/codebase\" rel=\"noreferrer\">jBPT</a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/google/guava/wiki/GraphsExplained\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Google Guava</a> if you need good datastructures only.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/jgrapht/jgrapht\" rel=\"noreferrer\">JGraphT</a> is a graph library with many Algorithms implemented and having  (in my oppinion) a good graph model. <a href=\"https://github.com/jgrapht/jgrapht/wiki/HelloWorld\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Helloworld Example</a>. License: LGPL+EPL.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://jung.sourceforge.net\" rel=\"noreferrer\">JUNG2</a> is also a BSD-licensed library with the data structure similar to JGraphT. It offers layouting algorithms, which are currently missing in JGraphT. The most recent commit is from 2010 and packages <code>hep.aida.*</code> are LGPL (via the <a href=\"http://acs.lbl.gov/software/colt/license.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">colt library</a>, which <a href=\"http://jung.sourceforge.net/download.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">is imported by JUNG</a>). This prevents JUNG from being used in projects under the umbrella of ASF and ESF. Maybe one should use the <a href=\"http://github.com/rortian/jung2\" rel=\"noreferrer\">github fork</a> and remove that dependency. <a href=\"https://github.com/rortian/jung2/commit/f4ca0cdcd3312589cbb48de7350b84cbff6067b9\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Commit f4ca0cd</a> is mirroring the last CVS commit. The current commits seem to remove visualization functionality. <a href=\"https://github.com/rortian/jung2/commit/d0fb491c0b5d2156e12df3a344521cfe7581c3d8\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Commit d0fb491c</a> adds a <code>.gitignore</code>.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/prefuse/Prefuse\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Prefuse</a> stores the graphs using a matrix structure, which is not memory efficient for sparse graphs. License: BSD</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.eclipse.org/gef/zest/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Eclipse Zest</a> has built in graph layout algorithms, which can be used independently of SWT. See <a href=\"http://git.eclipse.org/c/gef/org.eclipse.zest.git/tree/org.eclipse.zest.layouts/src/org/eclipse/zest/layouts/algorithms\" rel=\"noreferrer\">org.eclipse.zest.layouts.algorithms</a>. The graph structure used is the one of <a href=\"http://www.eclipse.org/gef/draw2d/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Eclipse Draw2d</a>, where <a href=\"http://help.eclipse.org/galileo/index.jsp?topic=/org.eclipse.draw2d.doc.isv/reference/api/org/eclipse/draw2d/graph/DirectedGraph.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Nodes are explicit objects</a> and not injected via Generics (as it happens in Apache Commons Graph, JGraphT, and JUNG2).</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 752115,
      "reputation" : 31,
      "user_id" : 753672,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2b09be9d5071e2f30a38716560c67e42?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Luc",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/753672/luc"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "community_owned_date" : 1420749501,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1380114424,
    "creation_date" : 1380114424,
    "answer_id" : 19005810,
    "question_id" : 51574,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you need performance, you might take a look at Grph. The library is developed in the French University and CNRS/Inria.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.i3s.unice.fr/~hogie/grph/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.i3s.unice.fr/~hogie/grph/</a></p>\n\n<p>The project is active and reactive support is provided!</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 220966,
      "reputation" : 431,
      "user_id" : 478686,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/62da96b3dfe500763e80358efca7e905?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Norbert Madar&#225;sz",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/478686/norbert-madar%c3%a1sz"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "community_owned_date" : 1420749501,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1390142853,
    "creation_date" : 1390142853,
    "answer_id" : 21218206,
    "question_id" : 51574,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Instructional graph algorithm implementations in java could be found here (by prof. Sedgewick et al.):\n<a href=\"http://algs4.cs.princeton.edu/code/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://algs4.cs.princeton.edu/code/</a></p>\n\n<p>I was introduced to them while attending these exceptional algorithm courses on coursera (also taught by prof. Sedgewick):</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/course/algs4partI\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.coursera.org/course/algs4partI</a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://www.coursera.org/course/algs4partII\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.coursera.org/course/algs4partII</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 355044,
      "reputation" : 38166,
      "user_id" : 693752,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 63,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1f9cd9b9bad9aa6115a1ed72433c180d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Snicolas",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/693752/snicolas"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "community_owned_date" : 1420749501,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1390638208,
    "creation_date" : 1390638208,
    "answer_id" : 21348339,
    "question_id" : 51574,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>It's also good to be convinced that a Graph can be represented as simply as : </p>\n\n<pre><code>class Node {\n   int value;\n   List&lt;Node&gt; adj;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>and implement most the algorithms you find interesting by yourself. If you fall on this question in the middle of some practice/learning session on graphs, that's the best lib to consider. ;)</p>\n\n<p>You can also prefer adjacency matrix for most common algorithms : </p>\n\n<pre><code>class SparseGraph {\n  int[] nodeValues;\n  List&lt;Integer&gt;[] edges;     \n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>or a matrix for some operations : </p>\n\n<pre><code>class DenseGraph {\n  int[] nodeValues;\n  int[][] edges;     \n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 55163,
      "reputation" : 1917,
      "user_id" : 165130,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 40,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/72fa3994a7ec56a8a030a98e808f96c4?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "alex",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/165130/alex"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "community_owned_date" : 1420749501,
    "score" : 9,
    "last_activity_date" : 1405504841,
    "last_edit_date" : 1405504841,
    "creation_date" : 1391194585,
    "answer_id" : 21487933,
    "question_id" : 51574,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>check out <a href=\"https://github.com/tinkerpop/blueprints/wiki\">Blueprints</a>:</p>\n\n<p>Blueprints is a collection of interfaces, implementations, ouplementations, and test suites for the property graph data model. Blueprints is analogous to the JDBC, but for graph databases.  Within the TinkerPop open source software stack, Blueprints serves as the foundational technology for:</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://pipes.tinkerpop.com/\">Pipes</a>: A lazy, data flow framework</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://gremlin.tinkerpop.com/\">Gremlin</a>: A graph traversal language</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://frames.tinkerpop.com/\">Frames</a>: An object-to-graph mapper</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://furnace.tinkerpop.com/\">Furnace</a>: A graph algorithms package</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://rexster.tinkerpop.com/\">Rexster</a>: A graph server</p>\n"
  } ],
